Notifications for Argo

Alexander Matyushentsev
Follow
Jan 20 · 6 min read

Notifications are an important part of the complete end-user experience but can be tricky to get right. Different organizations use different kinds of notifications services such as Slack, OpsGenie, or just good old email. There are dozens of different types of events that may need notification, so it is hard to predict all possible scenarios and optimize for all of them. Finally, every organization has different standards and may want to customize notification in a different way.

The Argoproj team has tried several different approaches to notifications during the past year. We’ve received a lot of feedback, learned a lot, and after much experimentation, we are happy to officially announce support for notifications! We’ve prepared a design and implemented a reusable Golang library that accommodates notifications functionality requirements of various Argo projects. The design document and the library defines configuration syntax, base concepts and ensures a consistent user experience in all Argo projects.

Argo CD Notifications

Argo CD is the first project that is getting notifications. Argo Rollouts is next, and Argo Workflows should get it soon thereafter. In this article, we are going to learn some basic concepts, get our hands dirty, and solve some real-life problems using Argo CD Notifications.

Wait? How about Argo Rollouts and Workflows. The good news is that the notifications design and configurations will be very similar for all Argo projects, so everything you learn today is going to be relevant for all Argo projects.

Getting Ready

First of all, we need a Kubernetes cluster with Argo CD. If you already have a cluster with Argo CD installed, feel free to move to the next step. If not let’s create a test cluster and install Argo CD. We will use the following guides:

  • Minikube: https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/
  • Argo CD: https://argoproj.github.io/argo-cd/getting_started/

If you are a Mac user then guides boil down to the following steps.

  • Install minikube and Argo CD CLI:
brew install minikube argocd
  • Create a new minikube cluster just for this demo:
minikube start -p argocd-notifications-demo
  • Create argocd namespace and install Argo CD:
kubectl create namespace argocd
kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj/argo-cd/stable/manifests/install.yaml

Done! Now we have a Kubernetes cluster with Argo CD and it is time to install and configure notifications!

Basic Notifications

Argo CD Notifications is an optional standalone project that should be installed in theargocd namespace. Let’s follow the Argo CD Notifications getting started guide that is available here. The installation consists of:

kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj-labs/argocd-notifications/release-1.0/manifests/install.yamlkubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj-labs/argocd-notifications/release-1.0/catalog/install.yaml

The first YAML file installed the controller that is responsible for notifications processing and the second configured notification triggers and templates. We are going to discuss triggers and templates shortly, but first, let’s configure integration with the notification service.

Notification Service Integration

Argo CD Notifications already supports Slack, Email, Telegram, Netgenie, Grafana, custom Webhooks, and the list keeps growing. You can find detailed instructions about each service in the Argo CD Notifications documentation.

For the sake of simplicity, let’s configure plain email integration since most of us use email:

  • Store your email account username and password in argocd-notifications-secret Secret:
export EMAIL_USER=<your-username>
export PASSWORD=<your-password>kubectl apply -n argocd -f - << EOF
apiVersion: v1
kind: Secret
metadata:
  name: argocd-notifications-secret
stringData:
  email-username: $EMAIL_USER
  email-password: $PASSWORD
type: Opaque
EOF

Note: If you are using Gmail, then you can create an app password by navigating to https://myaccount.google.com/apppasswords as described here: https://support.google.com/accounts/answer/185833?hl=en

  • The email service must be registered in argocd-notifications-cm ConfigMap:

To configure your Argo CD instance run the following command that patches the config map:

kubectl patch cm argocd-notifications-cm -n argocd --type merge -p '{"data": {"service.email.gmail": "{ username: $email-username, password: $email-password, host: smtp.gmail.com, port: 465, from: $email-username }" }}'

Done! At this point, Argo CD Notification is ready to use. The next step is to create an Argo CD application and subscribe to a notification.

Notification Subscription

The Argo CD Notification subscriptions are managed using notifications.argoproj.io/subscription annotation. Go ahead and create an application using the following command:

kubectl apply -n argocd -f - << EOF
apiVersion: argoproj.io/v1alpha1
kind: Application
metadata:
  name: guestbook
  annotations:
    notifications.argoproj.io/subscribe.on-sync-succeeded.gmail: $EMAIL_USERspec:
  destination:
    namespace: default
    server: https://kubernetes.default.svc
  project: default
  source:
    path: kustomize-guestbook
    repoURL: https://github.com/argoproj/argocd-example-apps.git
    targetRevision: HEAD
  syncPolicy:
    automated: {}EOF

As soon as the application is created, Argo CD reconciles and synchronizes application manifests. Time to check your inbox! You should get an email notification about successful synchronization.

Subscriptions, Triggers, and Templates

Now it’s time to step back and learn what we’ve configured in detail. Let’s look at the annotation that was applied to the guestbook application:

notifications.argoproj.io/subscribe.on-sync-succeeded.gmail: <email>

The annotation consists of the following parts:

  • notifications.argoproj.io/subscribe is an annotation prefix that indicates subscription
  • on-sync-succeeded is a trigger name that catches successful synchronization events
  • gmail is the name of the email-based service that we’ve configured
  • <email> is the recipient email address that should be notified

Everything should be clear except on-sync-succeeded. What is a trigger and why on-sync-succeeded ?

The trigger defines the condition upon which the notification should be sent. It continuously watches Argo CD application’s state and desires when a notification should be sent. Triggers are configured in argocd-notifications-cm, thesame as the notification service. The YAML below contains anon-sync-succeeded trigger configuration:

The when property contains an expression that evaluates the application and returns true of false.

The second interesting property issend. It contains a list of notification templates. The template is responsible for notification text generation and is also configured in the argocd-notifications-cm ConfigMap:

The templates might be more complex if you want to leverage advanced features of more complex notification services like Slack.

Together, templates and triggers are solving two important requirements: powerful customization for operators while giving users a better and more intuitive user experience. On the one hand, operators need full flexibility and the ability to configure additional triggers and fully customize notification messages while the end-users only have to apply an annotation to subscribe to a trigger and specify the recipient. You can learn more about the additional features of triggers and templates in Argo CD Notifications documentation.

If you've been following this exercise carefully, you may have noticed that we did not really configure theon-sync-succeeded trigger and theapp-sync-succeeded template. So where did they come from? We got them from the Triggers and Template catalog that contains the list of useful triggers and templates for Argo CD. The catalog was installed when we configured the Argo CD Notifications controller using the following command:

kubectl apply -n argocd -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/argoproj-labs/argocd-notifications/release-1.0/catalog/install.yaml

The catalog description is available in Argo CD Notifications documentation and defined in the catalog directory of the argoproj-labs/argocd-notifications repository.

What’s Next?

There are many more things you can do with Argo Notifications. The webhook integration is one of the most exciting features. Webhooks enable interesting use cases such as better integration with Github, triggering Jenkins jobs, and much more. If you have any issues with settings, there is a CLI tool that simplifies troubleshooting.

As you can see, notifications provides a great way to interact with users and other services! Right now, notifications are supported only by Argo CD but will be coming to the other Argo projects soon. Please stay tuned!
